<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06303056 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06303056 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  In a surprise, Thinking Machines Corp. will disclose today that it has adopteda chip-design standard created by Sun Microsystems Inc. for its new CM-5supercomputer. The new machine will be able to harness as many as 2,000 chipsbased on the SPARC microprocessor to work simultaneously on different streamsof instructions. Other companies are nearing completion of supercomputers tobe announced at an industry trade show starting Nov. 18. in Albuquerque, N.M.The new machines will mark a transition from today's single-processor machinesto &quot;massively parallel&quot; computers, which harness thousands or even tens ofthousands of off-the-shelf chips.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NEW SUPERCOMPUTER TO USE SUN CHIP DESIGN  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Financial Digest  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911029  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  106  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, October 29, 199100303056,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>